---------------------------------------------------------------------------
WORLD ROUND-UP
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GLOBAL: Unesco pulls plug on Philosophy Day in Iran

The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organisation
decided last week to pull the plug on another embarrassment to its
reputation, dissociating itself from this year=92s celebration of philosoph=
y,
to be held in Iran in less than two weeks, writes Steven Erlanger for The
New York Times.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113055216147

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

INDIA: Higher education spending to rise 13% yearly

India=92s expenditure on higher education will grow nearly 13% annually in
the next 10 years driven by the private sector, said a report released by
Human Resource Development Minister Kapil Sibal on Thursday, writes
Prashant K Nanda for LiveMint.com.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D2010111305512524

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Reluctance to study abroad a =91pressing issue=92

A new study suggests that Britain=92s economic future could be jeopardised
unless more students embrace overseas experience, reports The Guardian.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113055042123

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

AUSTRALIA: Biometric scans for foreign students=20

Foreign students will be included in a trial of biometric checks as part of
a wider campaign to weed out potential terrorists, writes Guy Healy for The
Australian.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113054946644

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CHINA: US exam botch frustrates Chinese students

Following the cancellation last month of thousands of Graduate Record
Examination scores in China due to administrative problems, a growing
number of Chinese students are speaking out about what they say is an
insufficient and ineffective response by the US company that runs the exam,
writes Mary Hennock for The Chronicle of Higher Education.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113054830766

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: For-profit drops suit against community college

When Fort Lauderdale-based Keiser University took one of Florida=92s
community college=92s to court last month for slander, the suit garnered
national attention as evidence of just how nasty the debate over for-profit
colleges had become, writes Michael Vasquez for The Miami Herald.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113054731694

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: Money fuels environmentalist boom on campuses

Dickinson College in Carlisle, Pennsylvania, has pledged to be completely
carbon-neutral by 2020. On the West Coast, the University of
California-Santa Cruz saves an estimated $300,000 on water each year by
eliminating trays in its dining halls. And the University of Georgia, which
subsidises public transportation on campus, now has nearly 30 student
organisations related to sustainability, writes Brian Wingfield for
Forbes.com.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113054635997

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

MEXICO: Comparative study makes case for universities

It can be lonely at the top, especially when it comes to global university
rankings. So in 2008, researchers at the National Autonomous University of
Mexico, the sole Mexican university to break into the top 200 in
international rankings, decided to see how their institution stacked up
against its rivals in Mexico, writes Marion Lloyd for The Chronicle of
Higher Education.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113054539947

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

SCOTLAND: Free higher education must end =96 report=20

Free higher education in Scotland is under threat after a report published
by Universities Scotland confirmed that tuition fees must be reviewed,
writes Kathryn Richardson for The Journal.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113054428560

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

ISRAEL: Minister halts Tel Aviv University funding

Israeli Minister of Finance Yuval Steinitz last week ordered Accountant
General Shuki Oren to immediately stop budget transfers to Tel Aviv
University because of =93salary irregularities=94, reports Globes.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113054419661

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

INDIA: Mumbai academics want Mistry book back

The University of Mumbai=92s Academic Staff Association wants Rohinton
Mistry=92s book, Such a Long Journey, to be reintroduced, writes Mihika Basu
for the Daily News & Analysis.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101113054251732


